2 Hemispherectomy vs Small resection

A total of 64 patients underwent a smaller resection, and 40 underwent hemispherectomy after PMC. Overall, patients undergoing hemispherectomy have a better outcome (as we would have expected). Seizure-freedom in the SLIM group is similar to my initial analysis on the first 30 patients, at about 30%.

Recurrence Seizure-free Row Total
Hemispherectomy 32.5% (13) 67.5% (27) 38.5% (40)
Smaller resection 70.3% (45) 29.7% (19) 61.5% (64)
Column Total 55.8% (58) 44.2% (46) 100.0% (104)

3 Does concordance predict seizure freedom? overall concordance. MRI vs PET concordance?

I think this is probably the most interesting part of the analysis. Using the âconcordance indexâ, we can see a clear pattern here: looks like 100% concordance much more frequently seen in the seizure-free group.

Seems like less of an issue for hemispherectomy compared to smaller resection though. Letâs see that alone:

What if we lump this index to discordant and concordant? An index of 0.9-1 is concordant while anything lower is discordant. The proportion of patients doing well is much higher in the high-concordance group.

Tabulating this, we do see a clear pattern based on the small resection only group.

recurrence
(N=45)		 seizure-free
(N=19)		 P-value
concord_category
high 2 (4.4%) 8 (42.1%) <0.001
low 40 (88.9%) 9 (47.4%)
Missing 3 (6.7%) 2 (10.5%)

Letâs plot a K-M curve. Unfortunately, we have very unequal follow-up times so the curves arenât plotting perfectly - e.g.Â the light line wouldnât drop off like that if we had more follow up on those patients. But overall I think you can appreciate that patients with concordant data do much better.

Finally, the most common type of tests done are MRI and PET. What if we looked just at that? Here, there are three categories and the best outcomes seem to be when area of PET abnormality matches MRI. There is a high rate of failure when PET abnormality extends beyond visible MRI lesion.

Looking at this in tabular view, P-value <0.05:

recurrence
(N=58)		 seizure-free
(N=46)		 P-value
pet_concord
mri>pet 18 (31.0%) 20 (43.5%) 0.01
pet=mri 12 (20.7%) 17 (37.0%)
pet>mri 28 (48.3%) 9 (19.6%)

Again, if we plot this on a KM curve, the line looks off because it drops off suddenly but thatâs a product of follow-up time. Those patients actually are doing quite well!

9 What are the main reasons that a small vs large surgery is chosen?

Nothing surprising here, I think the instrument was probably designed in a self-confirming way.

10 For those who undergo HEMI as a second stage, do they fair worse than having it at first stage?

A total of 28 patients underwent a second surgery. Much more common to go to a hemispherectomy as the second surgery (N = 21). Visually, I think outcome for a hemispherectomy as second surgery seems slightly better than when it is initially offered.

Still working on how to analyze this - basically need to get rate of seizure outcome as a function of time of hemispherectomy (surg1 vs surg2)
